im in arch with hyprland. i need to be able to put stuff from nvim or the command line onto the system clipboard. how?

Gemini said
Since you're on Hyprland, you're using Wayland, which means the old-school xclip or xsel utilities won't work out of the box. You need tools that speak the Wayland protocol.

The standard tool for this is wl-clipboard.

1. Install the Necessities
Open your terminal and grab the Wayland clipboard utilities and the provider for Neovim:

Bash
sudo pacman -S wl-clipboard xsel
(Note: I included xsel or xclip because some older apps still look for them, but wl-clipboard is your primary driver.)

2. Copying from the Command Line
Once installed, you can pipe anything into wl-copy and paste it with wl-paste.

To Copy: echo "Hello Hyprland" | wl-copy

To Paste: wl-paste > file.txt

Pro Tip: Alias these in your .bashrc or .zshrc for speed:

Bash
alias yank='wl-copy'
alias put='wl-paste'
3. Integration with Neovim
Neovim is smart, but it needs to know you want to use the system clipboard instead of its internal registers.

The Quick Fix (The "+" Register)
You don't actually need to change your config to copy to the system clipboard. In Neovim, the + register represents the system clipboard.

To copy a line: "+yy

To paste from system: "+p

The Permanent Fix (Syncing Everything)
If you want Neovim to always use the system clipboard (so y just works), add this to your init.lua or init.vim:

For init.lua:

Lua
vim.opt.clipboard = "unnamedplus"
For init.vim:

Vim Script
set clipboard=unnamedplus
4. Handling the "Selection" (Optional)
Wayland has two clipboards: the regular one (Ctrl+C / Ctrl+V) and the primary one (highlight to copy, middle-click to paste).

To copy to primary: wl-copy --primary

To paste from primary: wl-paste --primary

Note: If you find that copying from Neovim works but "disappears" when you close the terminal, you might need a clipboard manager like cliphist or copyq to keep the history alive in the background.

