Since you're on Hyprland, cliphist is the go-to choice because it handles both text and images beautifully and integrates perfectly with launchers like rofi or wofi.

Here is how to get it running and bound to a hotkey.

1. Install the tools
You’ll need cliphist to manage the database and xdg-utils to ensure it plays nice with your system.

Bash
sudo pacman -S cliphist xdg-utils
2. Update your Hyprland Config
You need to tell Hyprland to start the cliphist "watcher" every time you log in. This daemon listens for changes in your wl-clipboard and saves them to a local database.

Edit ~/.config/hypr/hyprland.conf and add these lines:

Bash
# Start the clipboard daemon
exec-once = wl-paste --type text --watch cliphist store 
exec-once = wl-paste --type image --watch cliphist store
3. Create a Keybind
Now you need a way to see your history. Most people use rofi or wofi as the menu. Replace rofi with wofi in the command below if that's what you use.

Add this to your hyprland.conf (e.g., using Super + V to open the clipboard):

Bash
bind = SUPER, V, exec, cliphist list | rofi -dmenu | cliphist decode | wl-copy
What this command does:

cliphist list: Grabs your history.

rofi -dmenu: Shows you the list in a searchable menu.

cliphist decode: Turns the selected item back into its original format.

wl-copy: Puts it back into your active clipboard so you can hit Ctrl+V or p.

4. Useful Management Commands
Sometimes you want to clear the slate. You can run these in your terminal:

Action	Command
Clear all history	cliphist wipe
Delete one item	cliphist list | rofi -dmenu | cliphist delete
View as images	cliphist list | rofi -dmenu -markup-rows
One Final Tip
Since cliphist stores data in a database (~/.cache/cliphist/db), your clipboard history will persist even after a reboot. If you copy sensitive passwords, remember to use cliphist wipe or specific delete commands.

