Gemini said
That is a classic "false positive" from Neovim.

Because you are likely running Neovim inside a terminal (which is inside a tmux session), Neovim sees that tmux has its own internal buffer and thinks, "Great! I'll just use that as the 'system' clipboard."

The problem? Tmux is not the system clipboard. If you copy something using +yy, it will stay inside tmux, and you won't be able to paste it into a web browser or another app in Hyprland.

The Solution
You need to override that "tmux" provider by installing the actual Wayland tool. Run this in your terminal:

Bash
sudo pacman -S wl-clipboard
Why this fixes it:
Neovim follows a specific priority list for clipboards. On Wayland, its search order looks like this:

wl-copy (Wayland Native - What you want)

waycopy (Alternative Wayland tool)

xclip / xsel (X11 tools - only work in Hyprland with XWayland)

tmux (The "fallback" it's currently using)

Once wl-clipboard is installed, Neovim will see wl-copy and automatically promote it to the top of the list, ignoring the tmux buffer in favor of the actual system clipboard.

Verify the change
After installing, restart Neovim and run:

Vim Script
:checkhealth provider
It should now say OK: Clipboard tool found: wl-copy.

Once you see that, "+yy will finally "leave" the terminal and be available for the rest of your Arch system.

